  <div class="process-list">
    <div class="process-item">
      <div class="process-icon">🍒</div>
      <div>
        <div class="process-name">Natural Process</div>
        <div class="process-subtitle">The whole fruit dries in the sun, unwashed</div>
        <p class="process-text">The coffee cherry is picked and left to dry whole — in the sun for weeks. The bean absorbs sugars and flavours from the fruit pulp as it dries. Araku Valley naturals are famous for this. Very common in Indian specialty coffee.</p>
        <span class="process-vibe">→ Very fruity, wine-like, sweet</span>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="process-item">
      <div class="process-icon">💧</div>
      <div>
        <div class="process-name">Washed Process</div>
        <div class="process-subtitle">Fruit is removed, bean is washed clean before drying</div>
        <p class="process-text">The fruit pulp is removed immediately after picking and the bean is thoroughly washed before drying. This gives you a "clean" cup — you taste the pure bean character. Most Chikmagalur and Nilgiris specialty coffee uses this method.</p>
        <span class="process-vibe">→ Clean, bright, consistent</span>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="process-item">
      <div class="process-icon">🍯</div>
      <div>
        <div class="process-name">Honey Process</div>
        <div class="process-subtitle">Some fruit pulp is left on the bean during drying</div>
        <p class="process-text">A middle path — some of the sticky fruit layer is left on the bean during drying. The result sits between natural and washed: some fruit sweetness, but also clarity. Increasingly popular with Indian specialty roasters. Notes of honey, stone fruit, mild sweetness.</p>
        <span class="process-vibe">→ Sweet, balanced, gentle</span>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="process-item">
      <div class="process-icon">🌬</div>
      <div>
        <div class="process-name">Monsooning</div>
        <div class="process-subtitle">Beans exposed to monsoon winds for weeks — uniquely Indian</div>
        <p class="process-text">Exclusive to India. Green beans are spread in open warehouses on the Malabar coast and exposed to monsoon winds for 12–16 weeks. They swell, change colour, and develop an incredibly earthy, musty, low-acid character. If you drink strong South Indian coffee, you've likely already had this.</p>
        <span class="process-vibe">→ Earthy, bold, zero acidity</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

