<!-- STEP 6 -->
<div class="guide-step" id="step6">
  <div class="step-header">
    <div class="step-num">06</div>
    <div class="step-title-block">
      <h2>Buying Smart</h2>
      <span class="step-sub">Where you buy matters as much as what you buy.</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="myth-box" style="margin-bottom:24px;">
    <p><strong>The single most important rule:</strong> A ₹500 bag of freshly roasted, freshly ground coffee brewed in a ₹400 South Indian filter will beat a ₹3,000 bag of pre-ground supermarket coffee brewed in a ₹25,000 machine. Freshness and grind quality matter more than equipment price.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="tips-list">
    <div class="tip-item">
      <div class="tip-num">1</div>
      <div class="tip-body">
        <h3>Look for the roast date — not the expiry date</h3>
        <p>Coffee goes stale, not dangerous. The "best before" date tells you nothing useful. You want to know when it was roasted. Freshly roasted coffee is at its best between 7–21 days after roasting. If there's no roast date on the bag, that's a red flag. Buy beans roasted within the last 3 weeks and use within 4–6 weeks of opening.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="tip-item">
      <div class="tip-num">2</div>
      <div class="tip-body">
        <h3>Buy whole beans — grind at home or at the shop</h3>
        <p>Ground coffee starts going stale within 15–30 minutes of grinding. Whole beans stay fresh for weeks. If you don't have a grinder, ask the roaster to grind for your specific brew method and buy only enough for 1–2 weeks at a time. Ask for: "Medium coarse grind for French press" or "Fine grind for South Indian filter."</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="tip-item">
      <div class="tip-num">3</div>
      <div class="tip-body">
        <h3>Buy direct from roasters</h3>
        <p>Indian specialty roasters who ship nationwide: Blue Tokai (most widely available, excellent Chikmagalur &amp; Araku range), Araku Coffee, Third Wave Coffee Roasters, Flying Squirrel (Coorg focus), Corridor Seven, Subko, KC Roasters. All have online stores and all print roast dates. If you have a local independent roaster — even better, the beans are freshest.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="tip-item">
      <div class="tip-num">4</div>
      <div class="tip-body">
        <h3>How to store your coffee</h3>
        <p>Keep in an airtight container, away from direct sunlight, heat, and moisture. Not in the fridge — moisture damages beans. Best is a dark, cool cupboard. Most specialty bags have a one-way valve — keep beans in the bag and squeeze out air before sealing. Buy small amounts frequently (250g every 2–3 weeks) rather than 1kg bags that sit for months.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="tip-item">
      <div class="tip-num">5</div>
      <div class="tip-body">
        <h3>Reading a specialty coffee bag — 5 things to check</h3>
        <p><strong>1. Roast date</strong> — is it recent? &nbsp;<strong>2. Origin</strong> — which region of India? &nbsp;<strong>3. Variety</strong> — Arabica or Robusta? &nbsp;<strong>4. Process</strong> — Natural, Washed, or Honey? &nbsp;<strong>5. Tasting notes</strong> — what does the roaster say it tastes like? A skilled roaster's tasting notes are usually accurate. Use them to guide your choice. Don't be shy: DM the roaster asking which bean suits your brewing method — they're usually very happy to help.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Cheatsheet -->
  <div class="cheatsheet">
    <div class="cheat-title">The Coffee <em>Cheatsheet</em></div>
    <div class="cheat-grid">
      <div class="cheat-item">
        <div class="cheat-q">I want strong coffee</div>
        <div class="cheat-a">Robusta or Robusta-Arabica blend. Dark-medium roast. South Indian filter or Moka Pot.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="cheat-item">
        <div class="cheat-q">I want fruity coffee</div>
        <div class="cheat-a">Araku Valley Arabica. Natural process. Light roast. Pour Over or AeroPress.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="cheat-item">
        <div class="cheat-q">I want café-style lattes</div>
        <div class="cheat-a">Chikmagalur Arabica. Medium roast. Moka Pot + handheld frother, or invest in an espresso machine.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="cheat-item">
        <div class="cheat-q">I'm a complete beginner</div>
        <div class="cheat-a">South Indian Filter (₹400) + Chikmagalur Arabica medium-dark roast freshly ground. Perfect starting point.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="cheat-item">
        <div class="cheat-q">I find coffee too bitter</div>
        <div class="cheat-a">Try light or medium roast. Try washed process Arabica. Try pour over method. Adjust one variable at a time.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="cheat-item">
        <div class="cheat-q">What water temperature?</div>
        <div class="cheat-a">Let boiling water sit for 30 seconds before pouring. About 93–95°C. Boiling water can over-extract and cause bitterness.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="cheat-item">
        <div class="cheat-q">How much coffee per cup?</div>
        <div class="cheat-a">1g coffee per 15–17ml water. For one cup (250ml): 15–17g of coffee. Adjust to taste.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="cheat-item">
        <div class="cheat-q">Should I add chicory?</div>
        <div class="cheat-a">Traditional South Indian filter coffee uses a 70:30 or 80:20 coffee-chicory mix. Pure coffee without chicory is smoother. Try both — both are valid.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
